## Background
We already have IP-based rate limiting implemented via express-rate-limit middleware (10 req/min per IP). Now we need to add user-based rate limiting to prevent individual Telegram users from overwhelming the system.

## Implementation Steps

1. Create a user-based rate limiter that works alongside our existing IP-based limiter:
   ```javascript
   // In-memory store for user rate limits
   const userRequests = {};

   // User-specific rate limit configuration
   const USER_RATE_LIMIT = {
     windowMs: 60 * 1000, // 1 minute window
     maxRequests: 5,      // 5 requests per minute
     message: "Please wait a moment before asking another question"
   };

   // Check if user has exceeded rate limit
   function checkUserRateLimit(userId) {
     const now = Date.now();

     // Initialize user record if not exists
     if (!userRequests[userId]) {
       userRequests[userId] = {
         count: 0,
         resetAt: now + USER_RATE_LIMIT.windowMs
       };
     }

     // Reset counter if window has passed
     if (now >= userRequests[userId].resetAt) {
       userRequests[userId] = {
         count: 0,
         resetAt: now + USER_RATE_LIMIT.windowMs
       };
     }

     // Check if limit exceeded
     if (userRequests[userId].count >= USER_RATE_LIMIT.maxRequests) {
       return {
         limited: true,
         message: USER_RATE_LIMIT.message,
         resetAt: userRequests[userId].resetAt
       };
     }

     // Increment counter
     userRequests[userId].count++;
     return { limited: false };
   }
   ```

2. Integrate user-based rate limiting into the message processing flow (while preserving the existing IP-based limiting):
   ```javascript
   // Update processMessage function to include user-based rate limiting
   async function processMessage(chatId, messageText, userId) {
     try {
       // Skip rate limiting for /start command
       if (messageText !== '/start') {
         // Check user-specific rate limit
         const rateLimitCheck = checkUserRateLimit(userId);
         if (rateLimitCheck.limited) {
           await sendTelegramMessage(chatId, rateLimitCheck.message);
           return;
         }
       } else {
         // Handle /start command
         await sendTelegramMessage(chatId, "Hello! I'm your TON AI Strategist. Ask me any crypto-related questions!");
         return;
       }

       // Existing message processing code...
       const n8nResponse = await forwardToN8n(messageText, userId);
       // ...
     } catch (error) {
       // Error handling...
     }
   }
   ```

3. Add a cleanup mechanism for the in-memory store to prevent memory leaks:
   ```javascript
   // Periodically clean up expired rate limit records
   setInterval(() => {
     const now = Date.now();
     for (const userId in userRequests) {
       if (now >= userRequests[userId].resetAt) {
         delete userRequests[userId];
       }
     }
   }, 15 * 60 * 1000); // Run every 15 minutes
   ```

4. Add configurable user rate limit via environment variables:
   ```javascript
   // Update .env.example
   // USER_RATE_LIMIT_WINDOW_MS=60000
